  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the gut twists, time is tissue!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nMidgut malrotation with volvulus is the correct answer. The classic presentation of a newborn with bilious vomiting and a 'corkscrew sign' on an upper GI series is pathognomonic for midgut volvulus, a life-threatening surgical emergency.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMidgut malrotation results from incomplete rotation of the embryonic gut, leaving the small bowel mesentery with a narrow base. This predisposes the bowel to twist around the superior mesenteric artery (SMA), causing a volvulus. This twisting obstructs the duodenum and compromises the SMA blood supply, leading to rapid bowel ischemia and necrosis. The 'corkscrew sign' on contrast study visually depicts the spiraling duodenum and proximal jejunum around the SMA, confirming the diagnosis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Meconium ileus presents with bilious vomiting and abdominal distension, but imaging shows dilated loops, a microcolon, and inspissated meconium, not a corkscrew. \nOption C (Incorrect): Jejunal atresia causes bilious vomiting and dilated bowel loops proximal to the obstruction, but the contrast study would show an an abrupt cutoff, not a corkscrew. \nOption D (Incorrect): Pyloric stenosis causes non-bilious projectile vomiting, typically later in infancy (3-6 weeks), and imaging shows an elongated pyloric channel and 'string sign.' \nOption E (Incorrect): Intussusception typically presents with intermittent abdominal pain and 'currant jelly' stools, and imaging shows a 'target sign' on ultrasound or 'coiled spring' on enema, not a corkscrew of the small bowel.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Key Clinical Feature | Key Imaging Feature |\n|---|---|---|\n| Midgut Volvulus | Bilious vomiting (newborn), abdominal distension | \"Corkscrew sign\" on UGI, absent duodenal C-loop |\n| Pyloric Stenosis | Non-bilious projectile vomiting (3-6 wks) | \"Target sign\" on US, \"string sign\" on UGI |\n| Jejunal Atresia | Bilious vomiting (newborn), abdominal distension | \"Triple bubble\" sign on X-ray, abrupt cutoff on UGI |\n| Intussusception | Currant jelly stools, intermittent pain (infant) | \"Target sign\" on US, \"coiled spring\" on enema |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Bilious vomiting + corkscrew = surgical emergency.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn an upper GI series, the 'corkscrew sign' is pathognomonic, showing the twisted duodenum and proximal jejunum. Intraoperatively, the small bowel will be twisted around the superior mesenteric artery, often appearing dusky or ischemic, and the cecum will be in an abnormal position (e.g., right upper quadrant).\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Pediatric Surgical Association (APSA) guidelines for neonatal intestinal obstruction (2020) emphasize urgent diagnosis and surgical intervention for midgut volvulus.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Meconium ileus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Midgut malrotation with volvulus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Jejunal atresia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Pyloric stenosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Intussusception | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 961171897-PEDIATRIC-SURGERY-MCQS-1.txt**\n",
