  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Peyer's patch hypertrophy: the infant's intussusception culprit.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption A, Peyer’s patch hypertrophy, is the correct answer. In infants, intussusception is most commonly idiopathic, but when a lead point is identified, it is frequently due to hypertrophied Peyer's patches, often following a viral illness.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nIntussusception occurs when one segment of the intestine telescopes into an adjacent segment, most commonly ileocolic. In infants, lymphoid hyperplasia, particularly of the Peyer's patches in the terminal ileum, can act as a lead point. These enlarged lymphoid tissues, often stimulated by viral infections, protrude into the bowel lumen, allowing the proximal bowel to be invaginated into the distal segment by peristalsis, initiating the telescoping process.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Meckel’s diverticulum is a common lead point for intussusception, but it is less common than lymphoid hyperplasia in infants and more frequently seen in older children or adults.\nOption C (Incorrect): Polyps are rare causes of intussusception in infants and are more typically found as lead points in older children or adults.\nOption D (Incorrect): Lymphoma is a malignant cause of intussusception, but it is a rare lead point, especially in infants, and not the most common.\nOption E (Incorrect): Hemangioma is an extremely rare vascular anomaly that can serve as a lead point for intussusception, but it is far less common than Peyer's patch hypertrophy in infants.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Idiopathic Intussusception (Infants) | Pathologic Lead Point (Children/Adults) |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Typical Age** | 3 months to 2 years | Older children, adults |\n| **Most Common Cause** | Lymphoid hyperplasia (Peyer's patch hypertrophy) | Meckel's diverticulum, polyps, tumors (benign/malignant), duplication cysts |\n| **Clinical Presentation** | Abdominal pain, vomiting, 'currant jelly' stools | Similar, but often more chronic or recurrent |\n| **Treatment** | Non-operative reduction (air/hydrostatic enema) | Often requires surgical reduction/resection |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Infant intussusception: think Peyer's patch, not pathology.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, intussusception appears as a 'target sign' or 'pseudokidney sign.' In the operating room, the classic finding is telescoped bowel, often with a palpable lead point such as a hypertrophied Peyer's patch in the ileocolic region.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) Clinical Practice Guideline: Management of Intussusception (2000/2018). It recommends air enema as the primary treatment for uncomplicated ileocolic intussusception.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Peyer’s patch hypertrophy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Meckel’s diverticulum | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Polyp | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Lymphoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Hemangioma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 961171897-PEDIATRIC-SURGERY-MCQS-1.txt**\n",
