  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't delay, or the testis will decay!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nImmediate surgical exploration is the correct management for testicular torsion within 6 hours. This approach prioritizes rapid detorsion and restoration of blood flow to prevent irreversible ischemic damage and preserve testicular viability.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nTesticular torsion occurs when the spermatic cord twists, compromising arterial blood supply and venous drainage, leading to ischemia. The window for testicular salvage is critically time-dependent, with viability rates significantly decreasing after 6-8 hours. Immediate surgical exploration allows for direct visualization, detorsion of the testis, assessment of viability, and bilateral orchiopexy to prevent recurrence, which is the definitive treatment.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Manual detorsion can be attempted as a temporizing measure, but it is not definitive and must be followed by urgent surgical exploration and orchiopexy. 'Elective surgery' is inappropriate as torsion is an emergency.\nOption C (Incorrect): Testicular torsion is an ischemic event, not an infection. Antibiotics are not indicated as primary treatment.\nOption D (Incorrect): Observation in cases of suspected testicular torsion will inevitably lead to testicular necrosis and loss, as it is a surgical emergency.\nOption E (Incorrect): Ultrasound is a valuable diagnostic tool to confirm torsion or rule out other pathologies, but it is not a treatment. Clinical suspicion alone warrants immediate surgical exploration, and delaying surgery for imaging can compromise testicular viability.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Testicular Torsion | Epididymitis | Torsion of Testicular Appendage |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Onset | Sudden, severe | Gradual | Sudden, less severe |\n| Pain | Scrotal, often radiates to groin/abdomen | Scrotal, dysuria | Localized to superior pole |\n| Cremasteric Reflex | Absent | Present | Present |\n| Prehn's Sign | Negative (no relief with elevation) | Positive (relief with elevation) | Negative |\n| Urinalysis | Normal | Pyuria, bacteriuria | Normal |\n| Ultrasound | Absent blood flow | Increased blood flow | Normal flow, 'blue dot' sign |\n| Management | Immediate surgical exploration | Antibiotics, NSAIDs | NSAIDs, observation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Time is testis. Suspect torsion, explore immediately.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, testicular torsion typically shows absent or significantly diminished blood flow to the affected testis on color Doppler. Intraoperatively, the twisted spermatic cord will be evident, and the testis will appear dusky, edematous, or frankly necrotic depending on the duration of ischemia. Detorsion should be performed, and viability assessed by warmth, color, and bleeding from small incisions.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guideline on the Diagnosis and Management of Testicular Torsion (2018): Recommends immediate surgical exploration for suspected testicular torsion.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Manual detorsion + elective surgery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Immediate surgical exploration | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Antibiotics | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Observation | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Ultrasound only | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 961171897-PEDIATRIC-SURGERY-MCQS-1.txt**\n",
