  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Wilms tumor: Ultrasound first, always.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe best initial investigation for a suspected Wilms tumor is an ultrasound of the abdomen. This non-invasive, readily available modality provides crucial information to differentiate a solid mass from a cystic lesion and assess the kidney.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nUltrasound is the preferred initial imaging due to its lack of ionizing radiation, which is paramount in pediatric patients. It effectively characterizes the renal mass (solid vs. cystic), evaluates the contralateral kidney for synchronous tumors, and can detect tumor thrombus extension into the renal vein and inferior vena cava (IVC). Its cost-effectiveness and widespread availability make it an ideal first-line diagnostic tool before more detailed staging with CT or MRI.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (CT scan) (Incorrect): While excellent for detailed staging, assessing lymph nodes, and detecting metastases, CT involves ionizing radiation and is typically performed after ultrasound for surgical planning, not as the initial diagnostic test.\nOption B (MRI) (Incorrect): MRI provides superior soft tissue contrast and is excellent for evaluating IVC involvement or complex cases, but it is more expensive, less readily available, and often requires sedation in young children, making it a secondary investigation after ultrasound.\nOption D (PET) (Incorrect): PET scans are not routinely used for the initial diagnosis or staging of Wilms tumor due to limited utility and high cost.\nOption E (X-ray) (Incorrect): A plain X-ray has very limited diagnostic value for a renal mass; it may show a mass effect or calcifications but cannot characterize the tumor or its extent.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Modality | Role in Wilms Tumor | Pros | Cons |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Ultrasound | Initial diagnosis, differentiate solid/cystic, assess IVC | No radiation, readily available, cost-effective | Operator dependent, limited staging detail |\n| CT scan | Staging, surgical planning, assess mets | Excellent detail for staging, lymph nodes, mets | Radiation exposure, contrast risks |\n| MRI | Staging, especially for IVC thrombus, complex cases | No radiation, superior soft tissue contrast | Requires sedation in young children, higher cost |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Ultrasound is the first step for pediatric abdominal masses.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a Wilms tumor typically appears as a large, heterogeneous, solid renal mass. It may show areas of necrosis or hemorrhage. Crucially, ultrasound can visualize tumor extension into the renal vein and inferior vena cava, which is vital for surgical planning.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nChildren's Oncology Group (COG) guidelines (current year) recommend ultrasound as the initial imaging modality for suspected Wilms tumor, followed by CT or MRI for detailed staging.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | CT scan | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | MRI | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Ultrasound abdomen | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | PET | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | X-ray | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 961171897-PEDIATRIC-SURGERY-MCQS-1.txt**\n",
