  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When you see calcifications in a kid's belly, think neuroblastoma first!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies Neuroblastoma as the pediatric abdominal tumor most commonly associated with calcifications on CT. This is a critical diagnostic feature that helps differentiate it from other common pediatric abdominal masses.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nNeuroblastoma originates from neural crest cells and can arise anywhere along the sympathetic chain, most commonly in the adrenal gland. The high incidence of calcifications (80-90%) is attributed to areas of necrosis, hemorrhage, and subsequent dystrophic calcification within the rapidly growing tumor. These calcifications are often punctate or amorphous and can be seen throughout the tumor, providing a strong imaging clue for diagnosis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Wilms tumor) (Incorrect): Calcifications are uncommon in Wilms tumor, occurring in only 5-15% of cases, and are typically peripheral.\nOption B (Hepatoblastoma) (Incorrect): Calcifications are seen in about 10-15% of hepatoblastomas, making them less common than in neuroblastoma.\nOption D (Mesoblastic nephroma) (Incorrect): Calcifications are rare in mesoblastic nephroma, a benign congenital renal tumor.\nOption E (Renal cell carcinoma) (Incorrect): While RCC can calcify, it is primarily an adult tumor, and pediatric RCC is rare. Calcifications are not as prevalent or characteristic in pediatric RCC as they are in neuroblastoma.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Neuroblastoma | Wilms Tumor | Hepatoblastoma |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Origin | Neural crest cells | Metanephric blastema | Hepatocytes |\n| Location | Adrenal gland, sympathetic chain | Kidney | Liver |\n| Calcifications | Very common (80-90%) | Uncommon (5-15%) | Uncommon (10-15%) |\n| Age at presentation | <5 years | 2-5 years | <3 years |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Neuroblastoma's calcifications are its signature on CT.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn abdominal CT, neuroblastoma typically appears as a heterogeneous mass, often crossing the midline, with characteristic speckled or amorphous calcifications. It may also encase vessels without necessarily invading them.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nChildren's Oncology Group (COG) Neuroblastoma Guidelines (e.g., ANBL1232, ANBL1531) recommend imaging with CT/MRI for diagnosis and staging, where calcifications are a key feature to identify.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Wilms tumor | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Hepatoblastoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Neuroblastoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Mesoblastic nephroma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Renal cell carcinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 961171897-PEDIATRIC-SURGERY-MCQS-1.txt**\n",
