  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When it's a kid and a kidney mass, think Wilms!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nWilms tumor (nephroblastoma) is the correct answer. It is overwhelmingly the most common primary renal malignancy in children, accounting for approximately 90% of all kidney cancers in this age group.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nWilms tumor is an embryonal tumor of the kidney that arises from primitive metanephric blastema. Its peak incidence is between 2 and 5 years of age, making it a hallmark pediatric malignancy. The tumor's rapid growth and potential for metastasis necessitate prompt diagnosis and multidisciplinary management, including surgery, chemotherapy, and sometimes radiation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (RCC) (Incorrect): Renal cell carcinoma is exceedingly rare in children and is primarily a malignancy of adulthood.\nOption B (Mesoblastic nephroma) (Incorrect): While the most common congenital renal tumor, mesoblastic nephroma is typically benign, though it can be locally aggressive, and is not the most common *malignancy* overall in children.\nOption D (Neuroblastoma) (Incorrect): Neuroblastoma is a common childhood malignancy, but it originates from neural crest cells, typically in the adrenal gland or sympathetic chain, not primarily the kidney itself.\nOption E (Lymphoma) (Incorrect): Lymphoma can involve the kidney secondarily, but it is not the most common primary renal malignancy in children.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Wilms Tumor | Neuroblastoma | Mesoblastic Nephroma |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Origin | Kidney (metanephric blastema) | Adrenal gland/Sympathetic chain | Kidney (mesenchymal) |\n| Malignancy | Malignant | Malignant | Benign (usually) |\n| Peak Age | 2-5 years | < 2 years | Congenital/Infancy |\n| Presentation | Abdominal mass, hematuria, hypertension | Abdominal mass, opsoclonus-myoclonus, Horner's | Abdominal mass (often prenatal) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Wilms tumor is the king of pediatric kidney cancer.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (ultrasound, CT, MRI), Wilms tumor typically appears as a large, well-circumscribed, heterogeneous renal mass with areas of necrosis, hemorrhage, and calcification. It often distorts the renal collecting system and can extend into the renal vein or IVC.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nChildren's Oncology Group (COG) AREN0532 (2006, updated) provides comprehensive guidelines for the treatment of Wilms tumor, recommending risk-stratified therapy based on histology and stage.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | RCC | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Mesoblastic nephroma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Wilms tumor | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Neuroblastoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Lymphoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 961171897-PEDIATRIC-SURGERY-MCQS-1.txt**\n",
