  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When a child's bones ache and their hormones rage, think neuroblastoma's stage!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Neuroblastoma. This diagnosis is strongly indicated by the classic triad of an abdominal mass, bone pain, and evidence of catecholamine excess in a child.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nNeuroblastoma is a malignancy of neural crest origin, arising from primitive sympathetic neuroblasts. These cells are precursors to the adrenal medulla and sympathetic ganglia, explaining the tumor's ability to synthesize and secrete catecholamines (epinephrine, norepinephrine, dopamine) and their metabolites (VMA, HVA). The abdominal mass typically represents the primary tumor (often adrenal or retroperitoneal), while bone pain is a common symptom of metastatic disease, as neuroblastoma frequently spreads to bone marrow and cortical bone.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Wilms): Incorrect. Wilms tumor is a renal tumor that presents as an abdominal mass but does not produce catecholamines or cause bone pain as a primary symptom.\nOption C (Hepatoblastoma): Incorrect. Hepatoblastoma is a liver tumor presenting as an abdominal mass but is not associated with catecholamine excess or primary bone pain.\nOption D (Lymphoma): Incorrect. While lymphoma can present as an abdominal mass and cause bone pain if marrow is involved, it does not produce catecholamines.\nOption E (Teratoma): Incorrect. Teratomas are germ cell tumors that can present as an abdominal mass but do not cause catecholamine excess or typically present with bone pain.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Neuroblastoma | Wilms Tumor | Hepatoblastoma | Lymphoma (Abdominal) |\n|:---|:---|:---|:---|:---|\n| **Origin** | Neural crest cells | Metanephric blastema (kidney) | Hepatocytes/biliary epithelium | Lymphocytes |\n| **Location** | Adrenal medulla, sympathetic ganglia (abdomen, chest, neck) | Kidney | Liver | Lymph nodes, GI tract, solid organs |\n| **Markers/Syndromes** | VMA/HVA elevation, N-myc amplification | Aniridia, hemihypertrophy, WAGR, Denys-Drash | AFP elevation, Beckwith-Wiedemann | LDH elevation, EBV (Burkitt) |\n| **Key Symptoms** | Abdominal mass, bone pain, periorbital ecchymosis, opsoclonus-myoclonus, catecholamine excess | Abdominal mass, hypertension, hematuria | Abdominal mass, precocious puberty (rare), jaundice | Abdominal mass, fever, weight loss, night sweats |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Abdominal mass + bone pain + catecholamines in a child = Neuroblastoma until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (CT/MRI), neuroblastoma often appears as a heterogeneous abdominal mass with calcifications (seen in >50%). MIBG (metaiodobenzylguanidine) scintigraphy is highly specific for neuroblastoma as it targets neuroendocrine cells. Intraoperatively, the tumor can be firm, nodular, and may be adherent to surrounding structures, often originating from the adrenal gland or retroperitoneum.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nChildren's Oncology Group (COG) Neuroblastoma Guidelines (e.g., 2020-2023): These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for the diagnosis, staging, risk stratification, and treatment of neuroblastoma in children.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Wilms | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Neuroblastoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Hepatoblastoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Lymphoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Teratoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 961171897-PEDIATRIC-SURGERY-MCQS-1.txt**\n",
