  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the bowel targets itself, it's intussusception!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Intussusception. The 'target sign' on ultrasound is a classic and highly specific finding for intussusception, representing the telescoping of one segment of bowel into another.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nIntussusception occurs when a proximal segment of bowel (intussusceptum) invaginates into a distal segment (intussuscipiens). On transverse ultrasound, this creates concentric rings of bowel wall and mesentery within the lumen of the outer bowel, appearing as a 'target' or 'donut' sign. This anatomical arrangement, with layers of edematous bowel and trapped mesentery, is what generates the characteristic hypoechoic and hyperechoic rings.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Meconium ileus) (Incorrect): This condition is typically diagnosed by abdominal X-ray showing dilated loops with a 'ground glass' appearance, and microcolon on contrast enema. Ultrasound does not typically show a target sign.\nOption C (NEC) (Incorrect): Necrotizing enterocolitis on ultrasound presents with bowel wall thickening, pneumatosis intestinalis (echogenic foci in the bowel wall), portal venous gas, and ascites, not a target sign.\nOption D (Volvulus) (Incorrect): Midgut volvulus is characterized by the 'whirlpool sign' on ultrasound, indicating twisting of the superior mesenteric artery and vein, not a target sign.\nOption E (Appendicitis) (Incorrect): Acute appendicitis on ultrasound shows a non-compressible, dilated appendix (>6mm diameter), wall thickening, periappendiceal fluid, and sometimes an appendicolith, but not a target sign.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Classic Ultrasound Sign | Other Key Features |\n|---|---|---|\n| Intussusception | Target sign / Donut sign / Pseudokidney sign | Currant jelly stools, colicky pain, palpable mass |\n| Midgut Volvulus | Whirlpool sign | Bilious emesis, abdominal distension, acute onset |\n| Appendicitis | Non-compressible, dilated appendix | RLQ pain, fever, leukocytosis |\n| NEC | Pneumatosis intestinalis, portal venous gas | Prematurity, feeding intolerance, bloody stools |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Target sign on US = Intussusception until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn transverse ultrasound, the 'target sign' for intussusception appears as concentric hypoechoic and hyperechoic rings, representing the edematous bowel walls and trapped mesentery of the intussusceptum within the intussuscipiens. This is a highly sensitive and specific finding.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Management of Intussusception (2019): Recommends ultrasound as the initial diagnostic modality for suspected intussusception due to its high accuracy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Meconium ileus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Intussusception | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | NEC | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Volvulus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Appendicitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 961171897-PEDIATRIC-SURGERY-MCQS-1.txt**\n",
