  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 No ganglia, no go: Hirschsprung's makes meconium slow!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nHirschsprung disease is the correct answer. The classic presentation of delayed meconium passage in a newborn, followed by an explosive gush of stool upon rectal examination, is highly suggestive of this condition due to the relief of functional obstruction.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHirschsprung disease is characterized by the congenital absence of ganglion cells in the distal bowel, typically starting from the internal anal sphincter and extending proximally. This aganglionic segment is tonically contracted and fails to relax, leading to a functional obstruction. The explosive stool upon rectal examination occurs when the examining finger passes through the spastic aganglionic segment into the dilated, stool-filled colon proximal to it, releasing the trapped stool and gas.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Pyloric stenosis) (Incorrect): Presents with non-bilious projectile vomiting, typically at 3-6 weeks of age, not delayed meconium.\nOption C (TEF) (Incorrect): Presents with choking, coughing, and cyanosis with feeds, often with excessive drooling, not bowel obstruction symptoms.\nOption D (NEC) (Incorrect): Presents with abdominal distension, bloody stools, and signs of sepsis, usually in premature infants, and is an acquired inflammatory condition.\nOption E (Malrotation) (Incorrect): Presents with bilious vomiting due to duodenal obstruction, often with abdominal pain, and can lead to volvulus, but not typically delayed meconium with explosive stool on rectal exam.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Key Features | Diagnostic Test | Treatment |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Hirschsprung Disease | Delayed meconium, explosive stool on DRE, functional obstruction | Rectal biopsy (gold standard), contrast enema | Surgical resection of aganglionic segment |\n| Meconium Ileus | Abdominal distension, bilious vomiting, inspissated meconium | Abdominal X-ray (ground glass), contrast enema (microcolon) | Gastrografin enema, surgery for complications |\n| Anal Atresia | Absent anal opening, no meconium passage | Physical exam, invertogram/cross-table lateral X-ray | Surgical repair (anoplasty/colostomy) |\n| Necrotizing Enterocolitis (NEC) | Abdominal distension, bloody stools, signs of sepsis, pneumatosis intestinalis | Abdominal X-ray | Medical management, surgery for perforation/failure to improve |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Delayed meconium + explosive DRE = Hirschsprung until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nA contrast enema would typically show a 'transition zone' where the narrow, aganglionic segment meets the dilated, normally innervated proximal colon. Intraoperatively, the aganglionic segment may appear normal externally but lacks peristalsis, confirmed by frozen section biopsy showing absence of ganglion cells.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) Section on Surgery. Recommends rectal biopsy as the gold standard for diagnosis and surgical resection of the aganglionic segment.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Pyloric stenosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Hirschsprung disease | ✅ Correct |\n| C | TEF | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | NEC | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Malrotation | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 961171897-PEDIATRIC-SURGERY-MCQS-1.txt**\n",
