  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Gas in the gut wall? Think NEC, call the surgeon!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C. Pneumatosis intestinalis is the classic and most specific radiographic sign of necrotizing enterocolitis (NEC). It represents gas within the bowel wall, a hallmark of bacterial invasion and tissue necrosis in the intestinal wall.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nNecrotizing enterocolitis (NEC) is an acute inflammatory disease of the bowel, primarily affecting premature infants. The pathogenesis involves intestinal immaturity, formula feeding, and bacterial colonization, leading to mucosal injury and gas production by bacteria within the bowel wall. This gas, trapped within the submucosa or subserosa, manifests as pneumatosis intestinalis on imaging, indicating transmural necrosis and impending perforation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The target sign is typically associated with intussusception on ultrasound, representing layers of bowel within bowel.\nOption B (Incorrect): The double bubble sign is characteristic of duodenal atresia or annular pancreas, indicating gastric and duodenal distension with no distal gas.\nOption D (Incorrect): While 'soap bubble appearance' can describe the pattern of pneumatosis intestinalis, it is not the classic *sign* itself. Pneumatosis intestinalis is the direct term for gas in the bowel wall.\nOption E (Incorrect): The corkscrew sign is pathognomonic for midgut volvulus on an upper GI series, indicating a twisted superior mesenteric artery and malrotated bowel.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition                 | Classic Radiographic Sign      | Description                                                              |\n| :------------------------ | :----------------------------- | :----------------------------------------------------------------------- |\n| Necrotizing Enterocolitis | Pneumatosis Intestinalis       | Gas within the bowel wall                                                |\n| Intussusception           | Target sign (US), Crescent sign (X-ray) | Bowel telescoping into adjacent bowel                                    |\n| Duodenal Atresia          | Double bubble sign             | Distended stomach and duodenum, no distal gas                            |\n| Midgut Volvulus           | Corkscrew sign (UGI)           | Twisted small bowel around superior mesenteric artery                    |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Pneumatosis intestinalis = NEC until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn plain abdominal X-ray, pneumatosis intestinalis appears as bubbly or linear lucencies within the bowel wall. Other findings may include dilated bowel loops, portal venous gas, and pneumoperitoneum (indicating perforation).\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) Clinical Report on Necrotizing Enterocolitis (2010). It outlines diagnostic criteria including radiographic findings like pneumatosis intestinalis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Target sign | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Double bubble | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Pneumatosis intestinalis | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Soap bubble appearance | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Corkscrew sign | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 961171897-PEDIATRIC-SURGERY-MCQS-1.txt**\n",
