  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pyloric stenosis: 3-6 weeks, a classic pediatric surgical emergency.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is 3-6 weeks because this is the classic peak age for the clinical manifestation of hypertrophic pyloric stenosis (HPS), as the pyloric muscle progressively thickens leading to gastric outlet obstruction. Symptoms typically become severe enough to warrant medical attention within this timeframe.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nInfantile hypertrophic pyloric stenosis (IHPS) is characterized by hypertrophy and hyperplasia of the muscular layers of the pylorus, leading to a narrowed lumen and gastric outlet obstruction. While the hypertrophy is thought to begin in utero, symptoms typically manifest when the obstruction becomes significant enough to cause non-bilious projectile vomiting, usually between 3 to 6 weeks of age. This progressive obstruction explains why symptoms are rare at birth and become more pronounced as the infant grows and the pylorus thickens further.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Birth) (Incorrect): Pyloric stenosis symptoms rarely present at birth as the hypertrophy is usually not severe enough to cause significant obstruction immediately.\nOption B (1–2 weeks) (Incorrect): While some cases may present this early, 1-2 weeks is generally before the peak incidence, which typically occurs later as the pyloric muscle continues to thicken.\nOption D (3 months) (Incorrect): By 3 months, most cases of pyloric stenosis would have already been diagnosed and treated, as the symptoms are usually severe and progressive.\nOption E (6 months) (Incorrect): Presentation at 6 months is exceedingly rare for pyloric stenosis; it would almost certainly have been diagnosed much earlier.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Pyloric Stenosis | Malrotation with Volvulus | Intussusception |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Peak Age | 3-6 weeks | First month of life | 3 months - 3 years |\n| Vomiting | Non-bilious, projectile | Bilious, often sudden | Non-bilious initially, then bilious |\n| Stool | Normal, or constipation | Normal, or bloody (late) | \"Currant jelly\" stools |\n| Abdomen | Non-distended, \"olive\" mass | Distended, tender | Sausage-shaped mass, colicky pain |\n| Metabolic | Hypochloremic metabolic alkalosis | Metabolic acidosis (ischemia) | Variable |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Pyloric stenosis: 3-6 weeks, projectile vomit, palpable olive.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, the diagnostic criteria for pyloric stenosis include a pyloric muscle thickness of >3-4 mm and a pyloric channel length of >14-17 mm. Intraoperatively, a thickened, elongated, and firm pylorus is observed, which is then incised longitudinally down to the submucosa (Ramstedt pyloromyotomy).\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) Clinical Practice Guideline: Evaluation and Management of Hypertrophic Pyloric Stenosis. These guidelines emphasize ultrasound for diagnosis and surgical pyloromyotomy as definitive treatment.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Birth | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 1–2 weeks | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 3–6 weeks | ✅ Correct |\n| D | 3 months | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | 6 months | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 961171897-PEDIATRIC-SURGERY-MCQS-1.txt**\n",
