  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Wilms' tumor: Lungs are the first stop on its metastatic journey.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Lung because Wilms' tumor, a a common pediatric renal malignancy, primarily spreads hematogenously, with the lungs being the most frequent site of distant metastasis. This understanding is crucial for accurate staging and effective treatment planning in affected children.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nWilms' tumor, or nephroblastoma, typically originates in the kidney and spreads via two main routes: direct extension and hematogenous dissemination. The rich vascular supply of the kidney facilitates early entry of tumor cells into the bloodstream. These circulating tumor cells often lodge in the pulmonary capillary beds, leading to lung metastases, which are detectable in approximately 10-20% of patients at diagnosis. The liver is the second most common site, usually via venous drainage.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Bone) (Incorrect): While bone metastases can occur in some pediatric cancers (e.g., neuroblastoma, rhabdomyosarcoma), they are rare in Wilms' tumor, typically indicating advanced or anaplastic disease.\nOption B (Brain) (Incorrect): Brain metastases from Wilms' tumor are exceedingly rare and usually signify widespread, aggressive disease, not a common initial metastatic pattern.\nOption D (Liver) (Incorrect): Liver is the second most common site of metastasis for Wilms' tumor, but it is less frequent than lung metastasis. Therefore, while possible, it is not the *most* common.\nOption E (Colon) (Incorrect): Metastasis to the colon from Wilms' tumor is extremely rare and not a recognized common metastatic pathway.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Tumor Type | Most Common Metastatic Sites |\n|---|---|\n| Wilms' Tumor (Nephroblastoma) | Lung, Liver |\n| Neuroblastoma | Bone, Bone Marrow, Liver, Skin |\n| Rhabdomyosarcoma | Lung, Bone Marrow, Bone |\n| Renal Cell Carcinoma (Adult) | Lung, Bone, Liver, Brain |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Wilms' tumor loves the lungs.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT scan, lung metastases from Wilms' tumor typically appear as well-defined, often multiple, round or oval pulmonary nodules. The primary renal tumor itself is usually a large, heterogeneous mass replacing normal renal parenchyma, often with areas of necrosis or hemorrhage.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nChildren's Oncology Group (COG) AREN0532 (for favorable histology Wilms' tumor) and AREN03B2 (for anaplastic Wilms' tumor) guidelines, 2006-present. These guidelines dictate staging, treatment protocols, and surveillance for Wilms' tumor, including management of metastatic disease.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Bone | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Brain | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Lung | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Liver | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Colon | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 961171897-PEDIATRIC-SURGERY-MCQS-1.txt**\n",
