  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Milk protein: a common culprit for infant's bloody stool.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Allergic colitis. This condition, often triggered by cow's milk protein, is the leading cause of bloody diarrhea in otherwise healthy infants, typically presenting in the first few months of life.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAllergic colitis, also known as food protein-induced proctocolitis of infancy (FPIAP), is a non-IgE mediated immune response to dietary proteins, most commonly cow's milk or soy. It manifests as streaks of blood or mucus in the stool, often with loose stools, in well-appearing infants. The inflammation is typically limited to the colon and resolves with elimination of the offending protein from the infant's diet or the mother's diet if breastfeeding.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): NEC (Necrotizing Enterocolitis) is a severe inflammatory condition primarily affecting premature infants, presenting with abdominal distension, feeding intolerance, and systemic signs, often leading to sepsis and perforation. While it causes bloody stools, it's not the most common cause of bloody diarrhea in *all* infants, especially healthy term infants.\nOption B (Incorrect): Hirschsprung disease typically presents with chronic constipation, abdominal distension, and failure to pass meconium. While Hirschsprung-associated enterocolitis can cause bloody diarrhea, it's a complication and not the primary presentation or most common cause of bloody diarrhea in infants overall.\nOption C (Incorrect): IBD (Inflammatory Bowel Disease) is rare in infancy and more commonly presents in older children and adolescents. Its presentation is usually more chronic and severe than allergic colitis, involving weight loss, growth failure, and persistent inflammation.\nOption E (Incorrect): Meckel's diverticulum typically causes painless rectal bleeding, often bright red, due to ectopic gastric mucosa causing ulceration. It does not usually present with diarrhea.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Typical Presentation | Age Group | Key Feature |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Allergic Colitis | Bloody streaks/mucus in loose stools, well-appearing | Infants (first 6 months) | Resolves with dietary protein elimination |\n| Necrotizing Enterocolitis (NEC) | Abdominal distension, feeding intolerance, bloody stools, sepsis | Premature infants | Systemic illness, pneumatosis intestinalis |\n| Meckel's Diverticulum | Painless bright red rectal bleeding | Infants/young children | Ectopic gastric mucosa, often intermittent |\n| Infectious Colitis | Acute onset bloody diarrhea, fever, vomiting | Any age, often infants/toddlers | Positive stool culture (e.g., Salmonella, Shigella) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Bloody diarrhea in a well-appearing infant? Think allergic colitis first.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nEndoscopy with biopsy for allergic colitis would show eosinophilic infiltration of the colonic mucosa, often with lymphoid hyperplasia and cryptitis, but these findings are non-specific. Imaging is typically not required for diagnosis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nESPGHAN (European Society for Paediatric Gastroenterology, Hepatology and Nutrition) guidelines on food protein-induced gastrointestinal allergies (2017) recommend elimination diets as the primary management for FPIAP.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | NEC | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Hirschsprung | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | IBD | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Allergic colitis | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Meckel | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 961171897-PEDIATRIC-SURGERY-MCQS-1.txt**\n",
