  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Hirschsprung's hallmark: a transition zone, not just a narrow colon.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, \"Transition zone.\" This finding on a contrast enema is the hallmark radiological sign of Hirschsprung disease, indicating the abrupt change in bowel caliber between the aganglionic and ganglionic segments.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHirschsprung disease results from the absence of ganglion cells in the distal bowel, leading to a functionally obstructed, spastic, and narrowed segment. Proximal to this aganglionic segment, the normally innervated bowel dilates due to the chronic obstruction. On a contrast enema, the 'transition zone' is the point where this narrowed, aganglionic distal colon meets the dilated, ganglionic proximal colon, creating a characteristic funnel or cone-shaped appearance. This radiological finding is critical for guiding the subsequent diagnostic full-thickness rectal biopsy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Microcolon) (Incorrect): A microcolon is typically seen in conditions causing disuse of the colon, such as severe meconium ileus or prolonged total parenteral nutrition, not directly in Hirschsprung disease.\nOption C (Corkscrew) (Incorrect): A corkscrew appearance of the small bowel is characteristic of midgut volvulus, indicating twisting of the mesentery around the superior mesenteric artery.\nOption D (Double bubble) (Incorrect): The double bubble sign on an abdominal X-ray is pathognomonic for duodenal atresia or annular pancreas, indicating obstruction at the duodenum.\nOption E (Target sign) (Incorrect): The target sign (or donut sign) on ultrasound is characteristic of intussusception, representing layers of bowel telescoping into each other.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Radiological Sign | Associated Condition | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| Transition Zone | Hirschsprung Disease | Abrupt change in bowel caliber from narrowed aganglionic to dilated ganglionic segment on contrast enema. |\n| Double Bubble Sign | Duodenal Atresia/Annular Pancreas | Two air-filled loops (stomach and duodenum) separated by the pylorus, indicating duodenal obstruction. |\n| Corkscrew Sign | Midgut Volvulus | Twisted appearance of the small bowel and mesentery, often around the SMA, on upper GI series. |\n| Target Sign | Intussusception | Concentric rings of bowel on ultrasound, representing bowel telescoping into itself. |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Hirschsprung = transition zone on contrast enema.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a contrast enema, the classic finding is a narrow distal aganglionic segment followed by a dilated, normally innervated proximal colon, with an abrupt 'transition zone' between them. This is often best visualized on lateral views.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Management of Hirschsprung Disease (2017) recommends contrast enema as the initial imaging study, followed by rectal biopsy for definitive diagnosis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Microcolon | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Transition zone | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Corkscrew | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Double bubble | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Target sign | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 961171897-PEDIATRIC-SURGERY-MCQS-1.txt**\n",
