  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Childhood cancer's top foe? Leukemia, from head to toe!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, Leukemia. This is because acute lymphoblastic leukemia (ALL) is by far the most common malignancy diagnosed in children, accounting for approximately 25-30% of all childhood cancers.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nLeukemia is a cancer of the blood-forming tissues, including the bone marrow and lymphatic system. It is characterized by the uncontrolled proliferation of abnormal white blood cells, which interfere with the production of normal blood cells. This rapid, systemic proliferation of malignant cells, rather than a localized solid tumor, contributes to its high incidence in the pediatric population. The underlying mechanisms often involve genetic mutations that disrupt normal hematopoietic development, leading to clonal expansion of immature leukocytes.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Wilms) (Incorrect): Wilms tumor (nephroblastoma) is a common kidney cancer in children, but it is less common than leukemia.\nOption C (Neuroblastoma) (Incorrect): Neuroblastoma is a common solid tumor originating from neural crest cells, typically in the adrenal glands, but it is less common than leukemia.\nOption D (Lymphoma) (Incorrect): Lymphoma, a cancer of the lymphatic system, is a significant childhood malignancy but occurs less frequently than leukemia.\nOption E (Hepatoblastoma) (Incorrect): Hepatoblastoma is a rare liver cancer in children and is far less common than leukemia.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Malignancy | Primary Site | Relative Incidence (Childhood) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Leukemia | Bone Marrow/Blood | Most Common (25-30%) |\n| CNS Tumors | Brain/Spinal Cord | Second Most Common (20%) |\n| Lymphoma | Lymphatic System | Third Most Common (10-15%) |\n| Neuroblastoma | Adrenal Gland/Sympathetic Nervous System | Common Solid Tumor (6-10%) |\n| Wilms Tumor | Kidney | Common Renal Tumor (5-7%) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: For childhood cancer, always think blood first.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nWhile leukemia is primarily diagnosed via bone marrow biopsy, imaging (e.g., ultrasound, CT) may reveal secondary findings such as hepatosplenomegaly (enlarged liver and spleen) or lymphadenopathy (enlarged lymph nodes) due to leukemic infiltration. Chest X-rays can show mediastinal widening from thymic or lymph node involvement, particularly in T-cell ALL.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nChildren's Oncology Group (COG) guidelines for Acute Lymphoblastic Leukemia (ALL) provide comprehensive recommendations for diagnosis, risk stratification, and treatment protocols, emphasizing a multidisciplinary approach to care.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Leukemia | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Wilms | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Neuroblastoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Lymphoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Hepatoblastoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 961171897-PEDIATRIC-SURGERY-MCQS-1.txt**\n",
